<br>
Rexfelix <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ugrimwyrd.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Grimwyrd</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 89<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/16/02 7:10:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=242.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Roleplaying's in dire straits</span><hr size=1> Bah! Thread after thread about roleplaying, and everyone misses the point.<br>
<br>
Quake can be a great roleplaying game!<br>
<br>
Heck, one of my favorite roleplaying games as a kid was Frogger. Sure it was single player. And there wasn't a lot of character development. But I WAS a frog when I played that game!<br>
<br>
Roleplaying is all about your state of mind. What matters is are YOU escaping your own life and getting into the character you're controlling.<br>
<br>
Most of these arguments really center around what are good &quot;multi-player&quot; roleplaying games, and that's where the trouble comes in. Not everyone can get into character in the same way at the same time.<br>
<br>
I have a very easy time envisioning myself as a human druid when I play on this server. And the reason I like this server, is because it's a lot less likely that someone will come up and ruin the illusion I've built in my mind.<br>
<br>
When people come up and are blatantly OOC and annoying, I suddenly lose track of the fact that I'm a human druid and remember that I'm a 30-something computer-gamer that should really be doing something more useful with my tim, lol.<br>
<br>
But that doesn't change the fact that &quot;I'm&quot; in control of whether I'm playing a role or not. Because it all comes down to each individual's ability to get into character.<br>
 <p>Grimwyrd Storm<BR>
(Lux Aeternam)<BR>
31st Human Druid of Karana<BR></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/umadrain.showPublicProfile?language=EN>madrain</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Kerran Lord</span><br>  Posts: 214<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/17/02 1:46:23 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=242.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Roleplaying's in dire straits</span><hr size=1> Eh...I disagree that EQ isn't a roleplaying game.  I very much think it's a roleplaying game.  It's just the majority of people who play it AREN'T roleplayers.  I've seen people roleplay in Half-Life and Quake II.  I imagine it's even in Quake III and UT.  Those are very much action games.  It takes people to make a roleplaying game, not a game to make a roleplaying game. <p><center><font size=+2><a href="http://pub66.ezboard.com/bmaidensfancy">Shiden Kaidan</a></font>
<br><font size=1><i><a href="http://www.neriak.com/">Tier'dal</a> <a href="http://interealms.com/shadowknight/">Knight</a></i></font> of the<a href="http://www.firiona-vie.com/"> Firiona Vie</a> Server
<br><font color=red>@}</font><font color=green>--,---'---</font>
<br><i>"Let nothing stand in the way of power."</i></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ukharras.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kharras</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/17/02 3:38:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=242.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Roleplaying's in dire straits</span><hr size=1> Being an avid gamer (still play tabletop at LEAST once a week and i've got kids now), and a former small game publishing industry professional, it pains me to say this but:<br>
<br>
Blame gaming companies for the near-extinction of RPGs.<br>
<br>
Just a short laundry list:<br>
<br>
Poor financial planning<br>
Bad collections decisions (only an idiot doesn't sue long-term delinquent creditors, I don't care how long you have done business with them) <br>
Bad Marketing<br>
Bad Customer Service<br>
Bad Accounting<br>
Bad Public Relations (DIRECT QUOTE (to the local news from a game company rep in the city where Shawn Novak lived): &quot;No self-respecting satanist I know would play Dungeons and Dragons!&quot;)<br>
Lack of basic sense (ok, look, you would have to have been a fucking idiot to not have seen UO at release and said 'It'll never work'... yet MULTIPLE game companies did)<br>
<br>
I'm not gonna name names, but...<br>
here are some excerpts:<br>
<br>
&quot;We aren't getting into the MMORPG business because CGM[computer gaming monthly] called it a 'golden coaster' (use the CD as a coaster).&quot; (the company was being asked to license an engine and game name to a currently successful computer company)<br>
<br>
&quot;I knew he was in bad financial shape (my distributor) but I felt bad witholding product from him or trying to collect my money; we have been friends for years&quot; (and now, you're friends in bankruptcy)<br>
<br>
From late 1997 to mid 1998s, more than 85% of the gaming industry's distrubutors went bankrupt, owing almost tens of millions of dollars to game manufacturers and publishers. The reasons are varied... some of it was caused by the UPS strike in 1997, some was caused by CCG speculation, some was just general mismanagement. <br>
<br>
Many publishers attempted to continue to do business as usual, not realizing they had just been dealt a mortal blow.<br>
<br>
Add to this the MMORPG movement and the already extant CCG boom and RPGs could not survive as they existed. The game companies did not react in a realistic manner to the change in the market.<br>
<br>
Tabletop RPGs will never actually die... but widespread published material is now a part of history. <p>Kharras Fain <BR>
Janitor<BR>
Crusaders of the Realm</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ukimayasilverbark.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kimaya Silverbark</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.alienexplorer.com/clipart/images5/wolf.pawprint2.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 53<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/17/02 7:50:36 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=242.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.bellsouth.net/coDataImages/bellsouthpwp/Groups/15/15568/pages/34736/Kimaya-60.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Roleplaying's in dire straits</span><hr size=1> 1) EQ <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> IS</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> a RolePlaying game!  We're just saying that, due to game mechanics, etc., it's not conducive to a pure RP experience.  No reason to not make the most of it though and RP to the best of our ability anyway.<br>
